What is Git?
-> Git is a distributed version control software system that is capable of managing 
   version of source code or data.

----------- Git Commands ----------

1. Configuration Commands
CMD: git config --global user.name "username"
CDM: git config --global user.email "useremail@gmail.com"

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

2. Git Initialization
CMD-1: git init
CMD-2: git init <directoryName>
CMD-3: git init --initial-branch=branchName
EX: git init --initial-branch=main
-> Initializes a new Git Repository in the current directory (folder)

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

3. Adding files to staging area
CMD-1: git add <file-name>
-> Adds a specific file to the staging area

CMD-2: git add .
CMD-3: git add --all
-> Adds all modified and new files to the staging area.

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

4. Git Status
CMD-1: git status
CMD-2: git status -v
CMD-3: git status -s
-> Shows current state of your Repository, including tracked and untracked files, modified files, and branch information.

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

5. Git Commit
CMD-1: git commit
-> Make commit and open text editor to write message.

CMD-2: git commit -m 'commit message'
-> Create a new commit in a Git Repository with a specific message. '-m' stands for message.
